[2026-03-10T21:50:57Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NQ3SdsCuJeMEQFk6CE1p1z","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package logstream\n     2→\n     3→import (\n     4→\t\"bytes\"\n     5→\t\"encoding/json\"\n     6→\t\"fmt\"\n     7→\t\"strings\"\n     8→)\n     9→\n    10→// ParseClaudeLine parses a single Claude Code stream-json line and returns\n    11→// the human-readable text it represents. If the line is a protocol event\n    12→// with no user-visible content, ok is false. Non-JSON input is returned as-is.\n    13→func ParseClaudeLine(line []byte) (text string, ok bool) {\n    14→\tline = bytes.TrimSpace(line)\n    15→\tif len(line) == 0 {\n    16→\t\treturn \"\", false\n    17→\t}\n    18→\tif line[0] != '{' {\n    19→\t\treturn string(line), true\n    20→\t}\n    21→\n    22→\tvar base struct {\n    23→\t\tType string `json:\"type\"`\n    24→\t}\n    25→\tif json.Unmarshal(line, &base) != nil {\n    26→\t\treturn string(line), true\n    27→\t}\n    28→\n    29→\tswitch base.Type {\n    30→\tcase \"assistant\":\n    31→\t\tt := extractAssistantText(line)\n    32→\t\treturn t, t != \"\"\n    33→\tcase \"result\":\n    34→\t\tt := extractResultText(line)\n    35→\t\treturn t, t != \"\"\n    36→\tcase \"content_block_delta\":\n    37→\t\tt := extractDeltaText(line)\n    38→\t\treturn t, t != \"\"\n    39→\tcase \"content_block_start\":\n    40→\t\tt := extractBlockStart(line)\n    41→\t\treturn t, t != \"\"\n    42→\tdefault:\n    43→\t\t// Skip system, user (tool results), and other protocol events\n    44→\t\treturn \"\", false\n    45→\t}\n    46→}\n    47→\n    48→// ParseClaudeStream converts raw Claude Code stream-json output into\n    49→// human-readable text. It extracts assistant text, tool call summaries,\n    50→// and error messages, discarding protocol-level events.\n    51→//\n    52→// If the input does not appear to be stream-json (no valid JSON lines\n    53→// detected), it is returned unchanged.\n    54→func ParseClaudeStream(raw []byte) []byte {\n    55→\tlines := bytes.Split(raw, []byte(\"\\n\"))\n    56→\tvar out strings.Builder\n    57→\tjsonLines := 0\n    58→\n    59→\tfor _, line := range lines {\n    60→\t\tline = bytes.TrimSpace(line)\n    61→\t\tif len(line) == 0 {\n    62→\t\t\tcontinue\n    63→\t\t}\n    64→\n    65→\t\tif line[0] != '{' {\n    66→\t\t\tout.Write(line)\n    67→\t\t\tout.WriteByte('\\n')\n    68→\t\t\tcontinue\n    69→\t\t}\n    70→\n    71→\t\tvar base struct {\n    72→\t\t\tType string `json:\"type\"`\n    73→\t\t}\n    74→\t\tif json.Unmarshal(line, &base) != nil {\n    75→\t\t\tout.Write(line)\n    76→\t\t\tout.WriteByte('\\n')\n    77→\t\t\tcontinue\n    78→\t\t}\n    79→\t\tjsonLines++\n    80→\n    81→\t\tif text, ok := ParseClaudeLine(line); ok {\n    82→\t\t\tout.WriteString(text)\n    83→\t\t}\n    84→\t}\n    85→\n    86→\tif jsonLines == 0 {\n    87→\t\treturn raw\n    88→\t}\n    89→\n    90→\treturn []byte(out.String())\n    91→}\n    92→\n    93→// extractAssistantText handles Claude Code \"assistant\" events.\n    94→// Extracts text content from message.content blocks.\n    95→func extractAssistantText(line []byte) string {\n    96→\tvar event struct {\n    97→\t\tMessage struct {\n    98→\t\t\tContent []struct {\n    99→\t\t\t\tType  string          `json:\"type\"`\n   100→\t\t\t\tText  string          `json:\"text\"`\n   101→\t\t\t\tName  string          `json:\"name\"`  // for tool_use blocks\n   102→\t\t\t\tInput json.RawMessage `json:\"input\"` // for tool_use blocks\n   103→\t\t\t} `json:\"content\"`\n   104→\t\t} `json:\"message\"`\n   105→\t}\n   106→\tif json.Unmarshal(line, &event) != nil {\n   107→\t\treturn \"\"\n   108→\t}\n   109→\n   110→\tvar parts []string\n   111→\tfor _, block := range event.Message.Content {\n   112→\t\tswitch block.Type {\n   113→\t\tcase \"text\":\n   114→\t\t\tif t := strings.TrimSpace(block.Text); t != \"\" {\n   115→\t\t\t\tparts = append(parts, t)\n   116→\t\t\t}\n   117→\t\tcase \"tool_use\":\n   118→\t\t\tparts = append(parts, \"\\n--- Tool: \"+formatToolCall(block.Name, block.Input)+\" ---\")\n   119→\t\t}\n   120→\t}\n   121→\tif len(parts) == 0 {\n   122→\t\treturn \"\"\n   123→\t}\n   124→\treturn strings.Join(parts, \"\\n\") + \"\\n\"\n   125→}\n   126→\n   127→// extractDeltaText handles content_block_delta events (streaming API format).\n   128→func extractDeltaText(line []byte) string {\n   129→\tif bytes.Contains(line, []byte(`\"text_delta\"`)) {\n   130→\t\tvar event struct {\n   131→\t\t\tDelta struct {\n   132→\t\t\t\tType string `json:\"type\"`\n   133→\t\t\t\tText string `json:\"text\"`\n   134→\t\t\t} `json:\"delta\"`\n   135→\t\t}\n   136→\t\tif json.Unmarshal(line, &event) == nil && event.Delta.Type == \"text_delta\" {\n   137→\t\t\treturn event.Delta.Text\n   138→\t\t}\n   139→\t}\n   140→\treturn \"\"\n   141→}\n   142→\n   143→// extractBlockStart handles content_block_start events (streaming API format).\n   144→func extractBlockStart(line []byte) string {\n   145→\tif !bytes.Contains(line, []byte(`\"tool_use\"`)) {\n   146→\t\treturn \"\"\n   147→\t}\n   148→\tvar event struct {\n   149→\t\tContentBlock struct {\n   150→\t\t\tType  string          `json:\"type\"`\n   151→\t\t\tName  string          `json:\"name\"`\n   152→\t\t\tInput json.RawMessage `json:\"input\"`\n   153→\t\t} `json:\"content_block\"`\n   154→\t}\n   155→\tif json.Unmarshal(line, &event) == nil && event.ContentBlock.Type == \"tool_use\" {\n   156→\t\treturn \"\\n--- Tool: \" + formatToolCall(event.ContentBlock.Name, event.ContentBlock.Input) + \" ---\\n\"\n   157→\t}\n   158→\treturn \"\"\n   159→}\n   160→\n   161→// formatToolCall formats a tool name and its input into a human-readable\n   162→// summary like Bash('ls -al') or Read('path/to/file'). If the input is empty\n   163→// or cannot be parsed, just the tool name is returned.\n   164→func formatToolCall(name string, input json.RawMessage) string {\n   165→\tif len(input) == 0 {\n   166→\t\treturn name\n   167→\t}\n   168→\tvar params map[string]json.RawMessage\n   169→\tif json.Unmarshal(input, &params) != nil || len(params) == 0 {\n   170→\t\treturn name\n   171→\t}\n   172→\n   173→\t// Pick the most informative parameter for each known tool.\n   174→\ttype paramSpec struct {\n   175→\t\tkey      string\n   176→\t\tmaxLen   int\n   177→\t}\n   178→\ttoolParams := map[string]paramSpec{\n   179→\t\t\"Bash\":    {\"command\", 80},\n   180→\t\t\"Read\":    {\"file_path\", 0},\n   181→\t\t\"Edit\":    {\"file_path\", 0},\n   182→\t\t\"Write\":   {\"file_path\", 0},\n   183→\t\t\"Glob\":    {\"pattern\", 0},\n   184→\t\t\"Grep\":    {\"pattern\", 80},\n   185→\t\t\"Agent\":   {\"description\", 80},\n   186→\t\t\"WebFetch\": {\"url\", 0},\n   187→\t\t\"WebSearch\": {\"query\", 80},\n   188→\t}\n   189→\n   190→\tspec, known := toolParams[name]\n   191→\tif !known {\n   192→\t\t// For unknown tools, try common parameter names.\n   193→\t\tfor _, fallback := range []string{\"command\", \"file_path\", \"pattern\", \"query\", \"description\"} {\n   194→\t\t\tif _, exists := params[fallback]; exists {\n   195→\t\t\t\tspec = paramSpec{fallback, 80}\n   196→\t\t\t\tknown = true\n   197→\t\t\t\tbreak\n   198→\t\t\t}\n   199→\t\t}\n   200→\t}\n   201→\tif !known {\n   202→\t\treturn name\n   203→\t}\n   204→\n   205→\traw, exists := params[spec.key]\n   206→\tif !exists {\n   207→\t\treturn name\n   208→\t}\n   209→\n   210→\tvar value string\n   211→\tif json.Unmarshal(raw, &value) != nil {\n   212→\t\treturn name\n   213→\t}\n   214→\n   215→\tif spec.maxLen > 0 && len(value) > spec.maxLen {\n   216→\t\tvalue = value[:spec.maxLen] + \"...\"\n   217→\t}\n   218→\n   219→\treturn fmt.Sprintf(\"%s('%s')\", name, value)\n   220→}\n   221→\n   222→// extractResultText handles result events (final output).\n   223→func extractResultText(line []byte) string {\n   224→\tvar event struct {\n   225→\t\tType   string `json:\"type\"`\n   226→\t\tResult string `json:\"result\"`\n   227→\t}\n   228→\tif json.Unmarshal(line, &event) == nil && event.Type == \"result\" {\n   229→\t\treturn event.Result\n   230→\t}\n   231→\treturn \"\"\n   232→}\n   233→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"be03ba05-685d-4063-a5b5-3cada1f11f8c","uuid":"c9383fb2-1621-44a2-99ad-2103d8a4a2bf","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/internal/logstream/parse.go","content":"package logstream\n\nimport (\n\t\"bytes\"\n\t\"encoding/json\"\n\t\"fmt\"\n\t\"strings\"\n)\n\n// ParseClaudeLine parses a single Claude Code stream-json line and returns\n// the human-readable text it represents. If the line is a protocol event\n// with no user-visible content, ok is false. Non-JSON input is returned as-is.\nfunc ParseClaudeLine(line []byte) (text string, ok bool) {\n\tline = bytes.TrimSpace(line)\n\tif len(line) == 0 {\n\t\treturn \"\", false\n\t}\n\tif line[0] != '{' {\n\t\treturn string(line), true\n\t}\n\n\tvar base struct {\n\t\tType string `json:\"type\"`\n\t}\n\tif json.Unmarshal(line, &base) != nil {\n\t\treturn string(line), true\n\t}\n\n\tswitch base.Type {\n\tcase \"assistant\":\n\t\tt := extractAssistantText(line)\n\t\treturn t, t != \"\"\n\tcase \"result\":\n\t\tt := extractResultText(line)\n\t\treturn t, t != \"\"\n\tcase \"content_block_delta\":\n\t\tt := extractDeltaText(line)\n\t\treturn t, t != \"\"\n\tcase \"content_block_start\":\n\t\tt := extractBlockStart(line)\n\t\treturn t, t != \"\"\n\tdefault:\n\t\t// Skip system, user (tool results), and other protocol events\n\t\treturn \"\", false\n\t}\n}\n\n// ParseClaudeStream converts raw Claude Code stream-json output into\n// human-readable text. It extracts assistant text, tool call summaries,\n// and error messages, discarding protocol-level events.\n//\n// If the input does not appear to be stream-json (no valid JSON lines\n// detected), it is returned unchanged.\nfunc ParseClaudeStream(raw []byte) []byte {\n\tlines := bytes.Split(raw, []byte(\"\\n\"))\n\tvar out strings.Builder\n\tjsonLines := 0\n\n\tfor _, line := range lines {\n\t\tline = bytes.TrimSpace(line)\n\t\tif len(line) == 0 {\n\t\t\tcontinue\n\t\t}\n\n\t\tif line[0] != '{' {\n\t\t\tout.Write(line)\n\t\t\tout.WriteByte('\\n')\n\t\t\tcontinue\n\t\t}\n\n\t\tvar base struct {\n\t\t\tType string `json:\"type\"`\n\t\t}\n\t\tif json.Unmarshal(line, &base) != nil {\n\t\t\tout.Write(line)\n\t\t\tout.WriteByte('\\n')\n\t\t\tcontinue\n\t\t}\n\t\tjsonLines++\n\n\t\tif text, ok := ParseClaudeLine(line); ok {\n\t\t\tout.WriteString(text)\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\n\tif jsonLines == 0 {\n\t\treturn raw\n\t}\n\n\treturn []byte(out.String())\n}\n\n// extractAssistantText handles Claude Code \"assistant\" events.\n// Extracts text content from message.content blocks.\nfunc extractAssistantText(line []byte) string {\n\tvar event struct {\n\t\tMessage struct {\n\t\t\tContent []struct {\n\t\t\t\tType  string          `json:\"type\"`\n\t\t\t\tText  string          `json:\"text\"`\n\t\t\t\tName  string          `json:\"name\"`  // for tool_use blocks\n\t\t\t\tInput json.RawMessage `json:\"input\"` // for tool_use blocks\n\t\t\t} `json:\"content\"`\n\t\t} `json:\"message\"`\n\t}\n\tif json.Unmarshal(line, &event) != nil {\n\t\treturn \"\"\n\t}\n\n\tvar parts []string\n\tfor _, block := range event.Message.Content {\n\t\tswitch block.Type {\n\t\tcase \"text\":\n\t\t\tif t := strings.TrimSpace(block.Text); t != \"\" {\n\t\t\t\tparts = append(parts, t)\n\t\t\t}\n\t\tcase \"tool_use\":\n\t\t\tparts = append(parts, \"\\n--- Tool: \"+formatToolCall(block.Name, block.Input)+\" ---\")\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\tif len(parts) == 0 {\n\t\treturn \"\"\n\t}\n\treturn strings.Join(parts, \"\\n\") + \"\\n\"\n}\n\n// extractDeltaText handles content_block_delta events (streaming API format).\nfunc extractDeltaText(line []byte) string {\n\tif bytes.Contains(line, []byte(`\"text_delta\"`)) {\n\t\tvar event struct {\n\t\t\tDelta struct {\n\t\t\t\tType string `json:\"type\"`\n\t\t\t\tText string `json:\"text\"`\n\t\t\t} `json:\"delta\"`\n\t\t}\n\t\tif json.Unmarshal(line, &event) == nil && event.Delta.Type == \"text_delta\" {\n\t\t\treturn event.Delta.Text\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\treturn \"\"\n}\n\n// extractBlockStart handles content_block_start events (streaming API format).\nfunc extractBlockStart(line []byte) string {\n\tif !bytes.Contains(line, []byte(`\"tool_use\"`)) {\n\t\treturn \"\"\n\t}\n\tvar event struct {\n\t\tContentBlock struct {\n\t\t\tType  string          `json:\"type\"`\n\t\t\tName  string          `json:\"name\"`\n\t\t\tInput json.RawMessage `json:\"input\"`\n\t\t} `json:\"content_block\"`\n\t}\n\tif json.Unmarshal(line, &event) == nil && event.ContentBlock.Type == \"tool_use\" {\n\t\treturn \"\\n--- Tool: \" + formatToolCall(event.ContentBlock.Name, event.ContentBlock.Input) + \" ---\\n\"\n\t}\n\treturn \"\"\n}\n\n// formatToolCall formats a tool name and its input into a human-readable\n// summary like Bash('ls -al') or Read('path/to/file'). If the input is empty\n// or cannot be parsed, just the tool name is returned.\nfunc formatToolCall(name string, input json.RawMessage) string {\n\tif len(input) == 0 {\n\t\treturn name\n\t}\n\tvar params map[string]json.RawMessage\n\tif json.Unmarshal(input, &params) != nil || len(params) == 0 {\n\t\treturn name\n\t}\n\n\t// Pick the most informative parameter for each known tool.\n\ttype paramSpec struct {\n\t\tkey      string\n\t\tmaxLen   int\n\t}\n\ttoolParams := map[string]paramSpec{\n\t\t\"Bash\":    {\"command\", 80},\n\t\t\"Read\":    {\"file_path\", 0},\n\t\t\"Edit\":    {\"file_path\", 0},\n\t\t\"Write\":   {\"file_path\", 0},\n\t\t\"Glob\":    {\"pattern\", 0},\n\t\t\"Grep\":    {\"pattern\", 80},\n\t\t\"Agent\":   {\"description\", 80},\n\t\t\"WebFetch\": {\"url\", 0},\n\t\t\"WebSearch\": {\"query\", 80},\n\t}\n\n\tspec, known := toolParams[name]\n\tif !known {\n\t\t// For unknown tools, try common parameter names.\n\t\tfor _, fallback := range []string{\"command\", \"file_path\", \"pattern\", \"query\", \"description\"} {\n\t\t\tif _, exists := params[fallback]; exists {\n\t\t\t\tspec = paramSpec{fallback, 80}\n\t\t\t\tknown = true\n\t\t\t\tbreak\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\tif !known {\n\t\treturn name\n\t}\n\n\traw, exists := params[spec.key]\n\tif !exists {\n\t\treturn name\n\t}\n\n\tvar value string\n\tif json.Unmarshal(raw, &value) != nil {\n\t\treturn name\n\t}\n\n\tif spec.maxLen > 0 && len(value) > spec.maxLen {\n\t\tvalue = value[:spec.maxLen] + \"...\"\n\t}\n\n\treturn fmt.Sprintf(\"%s('%s')\", name, value)\n}\n\n// extractResultText handles result events (final output).\nfunc extractResultText(line []byte) string {\n\tvar event struct {\n\t\tType   string `json:\"type\"`\n\t\tResult string `json:\"result\"`\n\t}\n\tif json.Unmarshal(line, &event) == nil && event.Type == \"result\" {\n\t\treturn event.Result\n\t}\n\treturn \"\"\n}\n","numLines":233,"startLine":1,"totalLines":233}}}
[2026-03-10T21:50:57Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01W2VYGFu9Lnibb6xzzqmeg9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I found the bug. Let me trace through the exact sequence:\n\n**Live streaming path (the one that's broken):**\n\n1. In `prompt.py:177-199`, Claude's stream-json output is read line by line\n2. `extractStreamText()` extracts text from `content_block_delta` events → returns plain text (e.g., \"Hello world\\n\")\n3. The plain text is accumulated in `lineBuf` until a newline is found\n4. Then `StatusWriter.Log(stepName, \"Hello world\")` is called\n5. This writes a JSON `StatusMessage` with `Type: \"log\"` and `Message: \"Hello world\"` to container stdout\n\n\n6. The daemon picks this up and broadcasts it as a `LogLine` with type \"llm\" and the content\n7. The SSE handler receives it and passes it to `parseLLMLogLine()`\n8. That function checks if the line type is \"llm\" and then calls `ParseClaudeLine()` on the content\n9. Since the content is plain text without JSON formatting, `ParseClaudeLine()` correctly returns the text as-is — so this part actually works!\n\nNow I'm wondering if the real issue is in `extractStreamText()` — it only handles `content_block_delta` events with text content and result events, but it completely ignores `assistant` events and `content_block_start` events. For tool uses especially, they wouldn't appear in the live stream at all since the function doesn't know how to extract them.\n\nExamining the `extractStreamText()` function more closely...\n\nChecking event parsing...\n\nI think the real issue might be that `cloche logs` without `--follow` doesn't work properly for active runs—the user might not realize they need the flag. Or more fundamentally, `StreamLogs` should be serving live content from active runs instead of just reading from disk files. Right now when you call `cloche logs <run-id>` while a run is still going, it looks for the completed `full.log` file that doesn't exist yet, falls back to sparse captured events, and returns almost nothing useful to the user.\n\nThe `--follow` path works because it connects directly to the SSE stream, so I think the fix is to make `StreamLogs` do the same thing—stream live logs from the broadcaster when a run is active.\n\nActually, wait. Re-reading the issue more carefully: \"Claude logs still aren't streaming - they only arrive after the step finishes.\" The key is \"after the step finishes,\" not after the whole run. So within a multi-step workflow, logs for a given step only show up once that step completes, not while it's running. Let me trace through what happens inside a single step—Claude's stdout gets read line by line, text deltas are extracted, and complete lines are sent through `StatusWriter.Log()`.\n\nThese log calls happen during execution and should reach the daemon in real-time via `docker logs -f`. But then after the step finishes, `Execute()` returns the raw stdout, and the step executor copies that to the log file and writes it to `full.log`—operations that bypass the broadcaster entirely. So the live stream should show Claude's output in real-time while the archived log gets the complete raw output after each step finishes. But if the live stream is already working, I'm not sure what the actual bug is here.\n\nLet me think about this differently—what should happen versus what actually happens when running `cloche logs --follow <run-id>`. The follow path connects to SSE at the stream endpoint, subscribes to the log broadcaster for active runs, receives `LogLine` events, parses them with `parseLLMLogLine()`, and since the content is already plain text, it returns it as-is and sends it as an SSE event. This should work fine, unless something else is going wrong. Let me trace through the SSE handler again...\n\nSetting up the broadcaster subscription...\n\nThe handler subscribes to the channel, then enters a loop that waits for incoming log lines. When a line arrives, it parses it, skips any protocol-only lines, marshals it to JSON, and flushes it to the client. The logic looks sound, but I'm noticing there's no initial data sent and no timeout handling—if a subscriber connects while the run is idle or between steps, they might be waiting with no feedback.\n\nLooking back at the actual problem: the logs aren't streaming live, they only show up after the step completes. The issue is that `logStepOutput` writes the raw Claude output to `full.log` with type \"llm\", which contains all the stream-json events. But the live streaming path only extracts and sends text deltas, filtering out tool calls, system events, and tool results. The user really just needs to see that the agent is actively working.\n\nWait, maybe the real issue is that `SetLogBroadcaster` isn't actually being called in the daemon setup, so the `--follow` path never gets connected in the first place.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2737,"cache_read_input_tokens":55853,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2737},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"be03ba05-685d-4063-a5b5-3cada1f11f8c","uuid":"45f2b890-8014-4885-be16-03c7dc95fbd1"}
