[2026-03-10T21:52:20Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_018S4gpZJ92YyfYjjXv2h82i","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_014vYw4zkvjwDoZEWMroZnrc","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/docs/plans/2026-03-03-next-features-design.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11320,"cache_read_input_tokens":16761,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":11320,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01FS5WAKvZ54ncrYpdy2SFQf","session_id":"7e3762fb-e565-4c0e-b9b1-9371ff7bfffd","uuid":"bfdcfed7-5b78-4165-b803-3f55ab2e6fe5"}
[2026-03-10T21:52:20Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014vYw4zkvjwDoZEWMroZnrc","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Next Features Design\n     2→\n     3→Date: 2026-03-03\n     4→\n     5→This document captures the design for the five features listed in PROJECT.md:\n     6→Orchestrator, Indicator Lights, Web Dashboard, Log Contents, and Container Deletion.\n     7→\n     8→## 1. Orchestrator\n     9→\n    10→**Goal:** Automate work dispatch — pull ready tasks from a task tracker, generate\n    11→prompts via LLM, kick off workflow runs, and manage the merge queue for landing\n    12→completed work.\n    13→\n    14→**Location:** Built into `cloched` (no new binary).\n    15→\n    16→**Components:**\n    17→\n    18→### TaskTracker Port\n    19→\n    20→New interface `ports.TaskTracker`:\n    21→\n    22→```go\n    23→type Task struct {\n    24→    ID          string\n    25→    Title       string\n    26→    Description string\n    27→    Labels      []string\n    28→    Priority    int\n    29→}\n    30→\n    31→type TaskTracker interface {\n    32→    ListReady(ctx context.Context, project string) ([]Task, error)\n    33→    Claim(ctx context.Context, taskID string) error\n    34→    Complete(ctx context.Context, taskID string) error\n    35→    Fail(ctx context.Context, taskID string) error\n    36→}\n    37→```\n    38→\n    39→First adapter: Beads. Future adapters: Jira, Linear, GitHub Issues.\n    40→\n    41→Tasks returned by `ListReady` are ordered by priority (highest first).\n    42→\n    43→### PromptGenerator\n    44→\n    45→Takes a `Task` and project context, calls the project's configured LLM to generate\n    46→a prompt suitable for the workflow. The generated prompt is passed to the workflow run\n    47→as the `--prompt` argument.\n    48→\n    49→### Orchestration Loop\n    50→\n    51→Event-driven, triggers on:\n    52→1. Daemon startup — check all projects for ready work.\n    53→2. Run completion — after a run finishes, check the completed run's project for more work.\n    54→3. `cloche loop` CLI command — manual trigger, checks all projects.\n    55→\n    56→On trigger:\n    57→1. For each registered project with orchestration enabled:\n    58→2. Query task tracker for ready work (priority-ordered).\n    59→3. Check in-flight run count against per-project concurrency limit.\n    60→4. For each available slot: claim the highest-priority task, generate prompt, dispatch run.\n    61→\n    62→### Configuration\n    63→\n    64→Per-project in `.cloche/config.toml` (or similar):\n    65→\n    66→```toml\n    67→[orchestration]\n    68→enabled = true\n    69→tracker = \"beads\"\n    70→concurrency = 1\n    71→workflow = \"develop\"\n    72→```\n    73→\n    74→### Concurrency\n    75→\n    76→Per-project limits. Project A with limit 2 and project B with limit 1 can have up to\n    77→3 runs in-flight simultaneously.\n    78→\n    79→### Merge Queue\n    80→\n    81→When a run completes successfully (`done` result), the orchestrator enqueues its\n    82→branch (`cloche/<runID>`) into a per-project merge queue.\n    83→\n    84→**Serialization:** Per-project. Each project processes one merge at a time. Different\n    85→projects can merge in parallel. Queue is FIFO.\n    86→\n    87→**Merge execution:** The orchestrator picks the next branch from the queue and hands\n    88→it to an LLM agent running on the host (not in a container). The agent operates in\n    89→a git worktree and:\n    90→\n    91→1. Pulls latest main into the worktree.\n    92→2. Merges the feature branch.\n    93→3. Resolves any conflicts.\n    94→4. Runs validation if configured (tests, build).\n    95→5. If clean: merges to main, cleans up the worktree, deletes the branch.\n    96→6. If unresolvable: reports failure.\n    97→\n    98→**On the host via worktree:** Merges need direct access to the real git repo. A git\n    99→worktree is created for the merge, then removed after completion. Lighter weight\n   100→than spinning up a container.\n   101→\n   102→**Failure handling:** If the merge agent can't resolve conflicts, the merge is marked\n   103→as failed. The branch is preserved. The user is notified via the dashboard/indicator\n   104→lights. No automatic retry — human intervenes.\n   105→\n   106→**Post-merge:** After a successful merge, the branch is deleted and the orchestrator\n   107→triggers a check for more work (same event-driven model as run completion).\n   108→\n   109→---\n   110→\n   111→## 2. Indicator Lights\n   112→\n   113→**Goal:** Per-project health indicators based on recent run history.\n   114→\n   115→### Health Calculator\n   116→\n   117→Domain-level function: given the last N runs for a project, return health status:\n   118→- **Green** — all runs passed\n   119→- **Yellow** — some runs failed\n   120→- **Red** — all runs failed\n   121→- **Grey** — no runs yet\n   122→- **Blue** — all runs currently in-progress (no completed runs in window)\n   123→\n   124→Window size N is configurable per-project, default 5.\n   125→\n   126→### API\n   127→\n   128→Extend `GET /api/projects` to include a `health` field per project:\n   129→\n   130→```json\n   131→{\n   132→  \"name\": \"my-project\",\n   133→  \"health\": {\n   134→    \"status\": \"yellow\",\n   135→    \"passed\": 3,\n   136→    \"failed\": 2,\n   137→    \"total\": 5\n   138→  }\n   139→}\n   140→```\n   141→\n   142→### CLI\n   143→\n   144→`cloche health` — table of all projects with health status, passed/failed counts.\n   145→\n   146→### Dashboard\n   147→\n   148→Colored dot next to each project name on the landing page.\n   149→\n   150→---\n   151→\n   152→## 3. Web Dashboard Enhancements\n   153→\n   154→**Goal:** Project-centric landing page with health indicators, run history, and quick\n   155→actions. Enabled by default.\n   156→\n   157→### Landing Page\n   158→\n   159→Replace the current runs-list with a project overview. Each project card shows:\n   160→- Indicator light (health status color)\n   161→- Success rate (e.g. \"8/10 recent runs passed\")\n   162→- Mini run history — last ~10 runs as colored dots (green/red)\n   163→- Active run count\n   164→- Quick actions: \"Trigger orchestrator\" button, \"View runs\" link\n   165→\n   166→### Default Activation\n   167→\n   168→Dashboard starts automatically with `cloched` on default port `:8080`.\n   169→Overridable via `CLOCHE_HTTP` env var. Disable with `CLOCHE_HTTP=off`.\n   170→\n   171→### Existing Pages\n   172→\n   173→Runs list and run detail pages preserved, accessible per-project from the landing page.\n   174→\n   175→---\n   176→\n   177→## 4. Log Contents\n   178→\n   179→**Goal:** Capture all output (LLM conversations, script output, status messages) in a\n   180→unified log stream. Real-time streaming for active runs, archived files for completed runs.\n   181→\n   182→### Unified Log Stream\n   183→\n   184→The agent captures everything chronologically to `.cloche/output/full.log` with\n   185→structured entries:\n   186→\n   187→```\n   188→[2026-03-03T10:15:00Z] [status] step_started: build\n   189→[2026-03-03T10:15:01Z] [script] + npm run build\n   190→[2026-03-03T10:15:02Z] [script] Build successful\n   191→[2026-03-03T10:15:03Z] [status] step_completed: build -> done\n   192→[2026-03-03T10:15:04Z] [status] step_started: implement\n   193→[2026-03-03T10:15:05Z] [llm] Claude: I'll start by reading the relevant files...\n   194→[2026-03-03T10:15:06Z] [llm] Claude: [tool_use: Read file src/main.go]\n   195→```\n   196→\n   197→LLM output and script output are included inline in the unified stream. This is the\n   198→primary view for understanding what's happening.\n   199→\n   200→### Per-Step Files\n   201→\n   202→Additionally, per-step files are written for convenience:\n   203→- `.cloche/output/llm-<step>.log` — LLM conversation for agent steps\n   204→- `.cloche/output/<step>.log` — script output (existing behavior)\n   205→\n   206→### Real-Time Streaming\n   207→\n   208→For active runs, the daemon pipes container stdout to web clients via Server-Sent Events\n   209→(SSE). The run detail page gets a live log viewer. LLM and script output are visible\n   210→in real-time, not just status changes.\n   211→\n   212→CLI: `cloche logs <run-id> --follow` streams the unified log in real-time.\n   213→\n   214→### Post-Run Archival\n   215→\n   216→On completion, log files extracted to `.cloche/<run-id>/output/`. SQLite index stores:\n   217→run ID, step name, log file path, size, timestamps.\n   218→\n   219→### CLI Enhancements\n   220→\n   221→`cloche logs <run-id>` shows the full unified log.\n   222→`cloche logs <run-id> --step <name>` filters to a specific step.\n   223→`cloche logs <run-id> --follow` streams in real-time.\n   224→\n   225→---\n   226→\n   227→## 5. Container Deletion\n   228→\n   229→**Goal:** Keep failed containers for debugging. Show retained containers in the dashboard.\n   230→CLI command to delete them.\n   231→\n   232→### Retention Policy\n   233→\n   234→- Failed runs: container always kept (automatic).\n   235→- Successful runs: container auto-deleted (existing behavior).\n   236→- `--keep-container` flag preserved: keeps container regardless of outcome.\n   237→\n   238→### Container Tracking\n   239→\n   240→When a container is kept, record in SQLite: Docker container ID, run ID, project,\n   241→creation time, status. Updated when container is deleted.\n   242→\n   243→### CLI Command\n   244→\n   245→`cloche delete <container-or-run-id>` — accepts Docker container name/ID or run ID.\n   246→Calls daemon via gRPC to remove the container and update the store.\n   247→Single container at a time.\n   248→\n   249→### gRPC\n   250→\n   251→New RPC: `DeleteContainer(container_id)` — daemon calls `docker rm` and updates store.\n   252→\n   253→### Dashboard\n   254→\n   255→Run detail page shows whether container is still available. If so, shows \"Delete\n   256→container\" button. Project overview shows count of retained containers.\n   257→\n   258→---\n   259→\n   260→## Feature Dependencies\n   261→\n   262→The features have some natural ordering based on dependencies:\n   263→\n   264→1. **Container Deletion** — standalone, no dependencies on other features.\n   265→2. **Indicator Lights** — standalone domain logic, needed by Dashboard.\n   266→3. **Log Contents** — standalone, changes agent + daemon. Needed by Dashboard for log viewer.\n   267→4. **Web Dashboard** — depends on Indicator Lights and Log Contents for full functionality.\n   268→5. **Orchestrator** — depends on a working task tracker. Largest feature. Can be developed in parallel with 1-3. Includes the merge queue subsystem.\n   269→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01FS5WAKvZ54ncrYpdy2SFQf","session_id":"7e3762fb-e565-4c0e-b9b1-9371ff7bfffd","uuid":"36453935-1b88-4b0b-8d4f-67a1349a4085"}
